{"title_page": "Dan Sallitt", "text_new": "{{short description|American filmmaker and film critic}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name         = Dan Sallitt\n| image        = Film Director Dan Sallitt.jpg\n| caption      = Sallitt on the set of [[The Unspeakable Act]]\n| birth_name   = \n| birth_date   = {{birth date and age|1955|7|27}}\n| birth_place  = [[Wilkes-Barre]], [[Pennsylvania]], United States\n| alma_mater   = [[Harvard College]]<br>[[UCLA]]\n| years_active = \n| occupation   = Filmmaker and film critic\n| website      = {{URL|panix.com/~sallitt}}\n| known_for    = \n}}\n\n'''Dan Sallitt''' (born July 28, 1955) is an American critic, screenwriter and film director known for his [[microbudget]] filmmaking<ref>{{Cite news | last=Hinojosa | first=Jos\u00e9 Sarmiento | url=https://desistfilm.com/dan-sallitt-microbudgets/ |title=Dan Sallitt: \"Micro-Budgets Are a Liberating Thing for Me\" |work=Desistfilm |date=March 7, 2019 | accessdate=March 3, 2020}}</ref> and [[cinephile]] film criticism.<ref>{{Cite news | last=Tuttle | first=Harry | url=http://screenville.blogspot.com/2010/04/auteurist-v-cinephile-dan-sallitt.html |title=Auteurist v. Cinephile (Dan Sallitt) |work=Screenville |date=April 23, 2010 | accessdate=March 3, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Early life ==\nSallit was born on July 27, 1955 in [[Wilkes-Barre]], [[Pennsylvania]].<ref name=\"city\">{{Cite news | last=Kushner | first=Daniel J. | url=https://www.rochestercitynewspaper.com/rochester/dan-sallitts-family-films/Content?oid=2571286 |title=Dan Sallitt's \"family films\" |work=[[City Newspaper]] |date=June 25, 2015 | accessdate=March 1, 2020}}</ref> He received a B.A. in Mathematics from [[Harvard College]] in 1976 and an M.F.A in Screenwriting from the [[University of California, Los Angeles]] in 1979.<ref>{{Cite news | last=Poli | first=Vincent | url=https://read.kinoscope.org/2019/10/18/adult-problems-an-interview-with-dan-sallitt/ |title=Adult Problems: An Interview With Dan Sallitt |work=Kinoscope |date=October 18, 2019 | accessdate=March 3, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\n=== Film criticism ===\nSallitt moved to [[Los Angeles]] in 1976, where he became first-string film critic for the [[Los Angeles Reader]] from 1983 to 1985.<ref name=\"reader\">{{Cite news | last=Sachs | first=Ben | url=https://www.chicagoreader.com/Bleader/archives/2013/05/17/an-interview-with-dan-sallitt-director-of-the-unspeakable-act |title=An interview with Dan Sallitt, director of The Unspeakable Act |work=[[Chicago Reader]] |date=May 17, 2013 | accessdate=March 3, 2020}}</ref> He has written film criticism for outlets including ''[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]]'', ''[[Chicago Reader]]'', [[MUBI]], [[Masters of Cinema]], and the [[Toronto International Film Festival]]. He maintains a film blog called ''Thanks for the Use of the Hall''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://sallitt.blogspot.com | title=Thanks for the Use of the Hall |access-date=March 3, 2020}}</ref>\n\nWhen [[Sight & Sound]] published their ''50 Greatest Films of All Time'' in 2012,<ref>{{cite news |last=Christie |first=Ian |url=http://www.bfi.org.uk/news/50-greatest-films-all-time |title=The 50 Greatest Films of All Time |work=[[Sight & Sound]] | publisher=[[British Film Institute]] |date=September 2012 |accessdate=March 3, 2020}}</ref> Sallitt was asked to submit a list of his top-ten films.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bfi.org.uk/films-tv-people/sightandsoundpoll2012/voter/699 |title=Dan Sallitt |work=[[Sight & Sound]] | publisher=[[British Film Institute]] |date=September 2012 |accessdate=March 3, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Filmmaking ===\nIn 1986, Sallitt wrote and directed his first feature film, ''Polly Perverse Strikes Again'', which he financed solely from his work as a film critic.<ref name=reader /> He moved to [[New York City]] in 1992,<ref name=reader /> and wrote and directed ''Honeymoon'' (1998), followed by ''All the Ships at Sea'' (2004).\n\nHe released ''[[The Unspeakable Act]]'' in 2012. It played several major international film festivals, including [[Rotterdam International Film Festival|Rotterdam]], [[Vienna International Film Festival|Viennale]], [[Karlovy Vary Film Festival|Karlovy Vary]], [[Edinburgh International Film Festival|Edinburgh]], [[Melbourne International Film Festival|Melbourne]], and BAMcinemaFest, won the Independent Visions Competition prize at the [[Sarasota Film Festival]],<ref>{{Cite news | last=Oleszczyk | first=Micha\u0142 | url=https://www.rogerebert.com/far-flung-correspondents/my-brother-my-love |title=My Brother, My Love |work=[[RogerEbert.com]] |date=July 13, 2012 | accessdate=March 3, 2020}}</ref> and was acquired for U.S. distribution by [[The Cinema Guild]].<ref>{{Cite news | url=https://www.blu-ray.com/news/?id=9752 |title=Cinema Guild Acquires Dan Sallitt\u2019s The Unspeakable Act |work=Blu-ray.com |date=October 16, 2012 | accessdate=March 3, 2020}}</ref> The film appeared on year-end top ten lists by [[Amy Taubin]], [[Jonathan Rosenbaum]], [[Adrian Martin]] and [[Ignatiy Vishnevetsky]], and was included in the afterword to the [[South Korea|Korean]] edition of Rosenbaum's ''Essential Cinema: On the Necessity of Film Canons''.<ref>{{Cite news | last=Rosenbaum | first= Jonathan | url=https://www.jonathanrosenbaum.net/2018/09/afterword-to-the-korean-edition-of-essential-cinema/ |title=Afterword to the Korean Edition of Essential Cinema (Updated) |work=jonathanrosenbaum.net |date=September 8, 2018 | accessdate=March 3, 2020}}</ref>\n\nHis fifth feature film, ''[[Fourteen (film)|Fourteen]]'', premiered in 2019 at the [[69th Berlin International Film Festival]],<ref>{{Cite news | last=Ehrlich | first=David | url=https://www.indiewire.com/2019/02/fourteen-review-dan-sallitt-berlinale-2019-1202042329/ |title=\u2018Fourteen\u2019 Review: Dan Sallitt\u2019s Low-Budget, Highly Affecting Portrait of Female Friendship \u2014 Berlinale |work=[[IndieWire]] |date=February 8, 2019 | accessdate=March 3, 2020}}</ref> and was picked up for U.S. distribution by Grasshopper Films.<ref>{{cite news | last=N'Duka | first=Amanda | url=https://deadline.com/2020/01/grasshopper-film-dan-sallitt-fourteen-acquisition-1202831635/| title=Grasshopper Film Nabs Berlin Film Festival Pic \u2018Fourteen\u2019 | date=February 15, 2020 | work=[[Deadline Hollywood|Deadline]] | accessdate=February 23, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Retrospectives and recognition ===\nIn 2013, [[Anthology Film Archives]] hosted a [[retrospective]] of his work in conjunction with the theatrical release of ''[[The Unspeakable Act]]''.<ref>{{cite news | last=Harris | first=Brandon | url=https://filmmakermagazine.com/65850-dan-sallitt-on-the-unspeakable-act/#.Xl5hmC0ZNT4 | title=Dan Sallitt on The Unspeakable Act | date=February 27, 2013 | work=[[Filmmaker Magazine]] | accessdate=March 3, 2019}}</ref> ''[[Film Comment]]'''s Jonathan Robbins noted that Sallitt's work was \"rooted in the films of [[Robert Bresson]], [[Eric Rohmer]], [[Jean Eustache]], [[John Cassavetes]], and [[Maurice Pialat]]\".<ref>{{cite news | last=Robbins | first=Jonathan | url=https://www.filmcomment.com/blog/review-the-unspeakable-act-dan-sallitt/ | title=Review: The Unspeakable Act | date=March 5, 2013 | work=[[Film Comment]] | accessdate=March 3, 2019}}</ref> Later that same year, a Sallitt retrospective was held at the Cineuropa Film Festival in [[Santiago de Compostela]], [[Spain]], and traveled afterwards to the CGAI cinematheque in [[A Coru\u00f1a]], Spain.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://cgai.xunta.gal/gl/programacion/ciclos/cineuropa-dan-sallitt | title=Cineuropa: Dan Sallitt | work=CGAI | accessdate=March 3, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, [[George Eastman House]] in [[Rochester, New York|Rochester]], [[New York (state)|New York]] held a retrospective called \"Three Weekends with Dan Sallitt.\"<ref name=city />\n\nIn 2019, Filmadrid hosted a retrospective of Sallitt's work.<ref>{{Cite news | url=https://www.audiovisual451.com/filmadrid-2019-dedica-sendas-restrospectivas-a-dan-sallitt-y-al-nuevo-cine-brasileno/ |title=Filmadrid 2019 dedica sendas restrospectivas a Dan Sallitt y al nuevo cine brasile\u00f1o |work=Audiovisual451 |date=April 25, 2018 | accessdate=March 1, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Filmography ==\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size: 95%;\" border=\"2\" cellpadding=\"4\" background: #f9f9f9;\n|- align=\"center\"\n! style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" | Year\n! style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" | Film\n! style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" | Notes\n|-\n| 1986 || ''Polly Perverse Strikes Again!'' || [[Directorial debut]]\n|-\n| 1998 || ''Honeymoon'' || \n|-\n| 2004 || ''All the Ships at Sea'' || \n|-\n| 2012 || ''[[The Unspeakable Act]]'' ||\n|-\n|rowspan=2| 2019 || ''[[Fourteen (film)|Fourteen]]'' || \n|-\n| ''Caterina'' || Short\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{imdb name|id=1908524|name=Dan Sallitt}}\n* [http://sallitt.blogspot.com Thanks for the Use of the Hall].\n* [https://mikionaruse.wordpress.com A Mikio Naruse Companion].\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sallitt, Dan}}\n[[Category:1955 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American film critics]]\n[[Category:American film directors]]\n[[Category:American male screenwriters]]\n[[Category:Harvard College alumni]]\n[[Category:UCLA Film School alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American filmmaker and film critic}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name         = Dan Sallitt\n| image        = Film Director Dan Sallitt.jpg\n| caption      = Sallitt on the set of [[The Unspeakable Act]]\n| birth_name   = \n| birth_date   = {{birth date and age|1955|7|27}}\n| birth_place  = [[Wilkes-Barre]], [[Pennsylvania]], United States\n| alma_mater   = [[Harvard College]]<br>[[UCLA]]\n| years_active = \n| occupation   = Filmmaker and film critic\n| website      = {{URL|panix.com/~sallitt}}\n| known_for    = \n}}\n\n'''Dan Sallitt''' (born July 28, 1955) is an American critic, screenwriter and film director known for his [[microbudget]] filmmaking<ref>{{Cite news | last=Hinojosa | first=Jos\u00e9 Sarmiento | url=https://desistfilm.com/dan-sallitt-microbudgets/ |title=Dan Sallitt: \u201cMicro-Budgets Are a Liberating Thing for Me\u201d |work=Desistfilm |date=March 7, 2019 | accessdate=March 3, 2020}}</ref> and [[cinephile]] film criticism.<ref>{{Cite news | last=Tuttle | first=Harry | url=http://screenville.blogspot.com/2010/04/auteurist-v-cinephile-dan-sallitt.html |title=Auteurist v. Cinephile (Dan Sallitt) |work=Screenville |date=April 23, 2010 | accessdate=March 3, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Early Life ==\nSallit was born on July 27, 1955 in [[Wilkes-Barre]], [[Pennsylvania]].<ref name=\"city\">{{Cite news | last=Kushner | first=Daniel J. | url=https://www.rochestercitynewspaper.com/rochester/dan-sallitts-family-films/Content?oid=2571286 |title=Dan Sallitt's \"family films\" |work=[[City Newspaper]] |date=June 25, 2015 | accessdate=March 1, 2020}}</ref> He received a B.A. in Mathematics from [[Harvard College]] in 1976 and an M.F.A in Screenwriting from the [[University of California, Los Angeles]] in 1979.<ref>{{Cite news | last=Poli | first=Vincent | url=https://read.kinoscope.org/2019/10/18/adult-problems-an-interview-with-dan-sallitt/ |title=Adult Problems: An Interview With Dan Sallitt |work=Kinoscope |date=October 18, 2019 | accessdate=March 3, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\n=== Film criticism ===\nSallitt moved to [[Los Angeles]] in 1976, where he became first-string film critic for the [[Los Angeles Reader]] from 1983 to 1985.<ref name=\"reader\">{{Cite news | last=Sachs | first=Ben | url=https://www.chicagoreader.com/Bleader/archives/2013/05/17/an-interview-with-dan-sallitt-director-of-the-unspeakable-act |title=An interview with Dan Sallitt, director of The Unspeakable Act |work=[[Chicago Reader]] |date=May 17, 2013 | accessdate=March 3, 2020}}</ref> He has written film criticism for outlets including ''[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]]'', ''[[Chicago Reader]]'', [[MUBI]], [[Masters of Cinema]], and the [[Toronto International Film Festival]]. He maintains a film blog called ''Thanks for the Use of the Hall''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://sallitt.blogspot.com | title=Thanks for the Use of the Hall |access-date=March 3, 2020}}</ref>\n\nWhen [[Sight & Sound]] published their ''50 Greatest Films of All Time'' in 2012,<ref>{{cite news |last=Christie |first=Ian |url=http://www.bfi.org.uk/news/50-greatest-films-all-time |title=The 50 Greatest Films of All Time |work=[[Sight & Sound]] | publisher=[[British Film Institute]] |date=September 2012 |accessdate=March 3, 2020}}</ref> Sallitt was asked to submit a list of his top-ten films.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bfi.org.uk/films-tv-people/sightandsoundpoll2012/voter/699 |title=Dan Sallitt |work=[[Sight & Sound]] | publisher=[[British Film Institute]] |date=September 2012 |accessdate=March 3, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Filmmaking ===\nIn 1986, Sallitt wrote and directed his first feature film, ''Polly Perverse Strikes Again'', which he financed solely from his work as a film critic.<ref name=reader /> He moved to [[New York City]] in 1992,<ref name=reader /> and wrote and directed ''Honeymoon'' (1998), followed by ''All the Ships at Sea'' (2004).\n\nHe released ''[[The Unspeakable Act]]'' in 2012. It played several major international film festivals, including [[Rotterdam International Film Festival|Rotterdam]], [[Vienna International Film Festival| Viennale]], [[Karlovy Vary Film Festival|Karlovy Vary]], [[Edinburgh International Film Festival|Edinburgh]], [[Melbourne International Film Festival| Melbourne]], and BAMcinemaFest, won the Independent Visions Competition prize at the [[Sarasota Film Festival]],<ref>{{Cite news | last=Oleszczyk | first=Micha\u0142 | url=https://www.rogerebert.com/far-flung-correspondents/my-brother-my-love |title=My Brother, My Love |work=[[RogerEbert.com]] |date=July 13, 2012 | accessdate=March 3, 2020}}</ref> and was acquired for U.S. distribution by [[The Cinema Guild]].<ref>{{Cite news | url=https://www.blu-ray.com/news/?id=9752 |title=Cinema Guild Acquires Dan Sallitt\u2019s The Unspeakable Act |work=Blu-ray.com |date=October 16, 2012 | accessdate=March 3, 2020}}</ref> The film appeared on year-end top ten lists by [[Amy Taubin]], [[Jonathan Rosenbaum]], [[Adrian Martin]] and [[Ignatiy Vishnevetsky]], and was included in the afterword to the [[South Korea|Korean]] edition of Rosenbaum's ''Essential Cinema: On the Necessity of Film Canons''.<ref>{{Cite news | last=Rosenbaum | first= Jonathan | url=https://www.jonathanrosenbaum.net/2018/09/afterword-to-the-korean-edition-of-essential-cinema/ |title=Afterword to the Korean Edition of Essential Cinema (Updated) |work=jonathanrosenbaum.net |date=September 8, 2018 | accessdate=March 3, 2020}}</ref>\n\nHis fifth feature film, ''[[Fourteen (film)|Fourteen]]'', premiered in 2019 at the [[69th Berlin International Film Festival]],<ref>{{Cite news | last=Ehrlich | first=David | url=https://www.indiewire.com/2019/02/fourteen-review-dan-sallitt-berlinale-2019-1202042329/ |title=\u2018Fourteen\u2019 Review: Dan Sallitt\u2019s Low-Budget, Highly Affecting Portrait of Female Friendship \u2014 Berlinale |work=[[IndieWire]] |date=February 8, 2019 | accessdate=March 3, 2020}}</ref> and was picked up for U.S. distribution by Grasshopper Films.<ref>{{cite news | last=N'Duka | first=Amanda | url=https://deadline.com/2020/01/grasshopper-film-dan-sallitt-fourteen-acquisition-1202831635/| title=Grasshopper Film Nabs Berlin Film Festival Pic \u2018Fourteen\u2019 | date=February 15, 2020 | work=[[Deadline Hollywood|Deadline]] | accessdate=February 23, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Retrospectives and recognition ===\nIn 2013, [[Anthology Film Archives]] hosted a [[retrospective]] of his work in conjunction with the theatrical release of ''[[The Unspeakable Act]]''.<ref>{{cite news | last=Harris | first=Brandon | url=https://filmmakermagazine.com/65850-dan-sallitt-on-the-unspeakable-act/#.Xl5hmC0ZNT4 | title=Dan Sallitt on The Unspeakable Act | date=February 27, 2013 | work=[[Filmmaker Magazine]] | accessdate=March 3, 2019}}</ref> ''[[Film Comment]]'''s Jonathan Robbins noted that Sallitt's work was \"rooted in the films of [[Robert Bresson]], [[Eric Rohmer]], [[Jean Eustache]], [[John Cassavetes]], and [[Maurice Pialat]]\".<ref>{{cite news | last=Robbins | first=Jonathan | url=https://www.filmcomment.com/blog/review-the-unspeakable-act-dan-sallitt/ | title=Review: The Unspeakable Act | date=March 5, 2013 | work=[[Film Comment]] | accessdate=March 3, 2019}}</ref> Later that same year, a Sallitt retrospective was held at the Cineuropa Film Festival in [[Santiago de Compostela]], [[Spain]], and traveled afterwards to the CGAI cinematheque in [[A Coru\u00f1a]], Spain.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://cgai.xunta.gal/gl/programacion/ciclos/cineuropa-dan-sallitt | title=Cineuropa: Dan Sallitt | work=CGAI | accessdate=March 3, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, [[George Eastman House]] in [[Rochester, New York|Rochester]], [[New York (state)|New York]] held a retrospective called \"Three Weekends with Dan Sallitt.\"<ref name=city /> \n\nIn 2019, Filmadrid hosted a retrospective of Sallitt's work.<ref>{{Cite news | url=https://www.audiovisual451.com/filmadrid-2019-dedica-sendas-restrospectivas-a-dan-sallitt-y-al-nuevo-cine-brasileno/ |title=Filmadrid 2019 dedica sendas restrospectivas a Dan Sallitt y al nuevo cine brasile\u00f1o |work=Audiovisual451 |date=April 25, 2018 | accessdate=March 1, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Filmography ==\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size: 95%;\" border=\"2\" cellpadding=\"4\" background: #f9f9f9;\n|- align=\"center\"\n! style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" | Year\n! style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" | Film\n! style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" | Notes\n|-\n| 1986 || ''Polly Perverse Strikes Again!'' || [[Directorial debut]]\n|-\n| 1998 || ''Honeymoon'' || \n|-\n| 2004 || ''All the Ships at Sea'' || \n|-\n| 2012 || ''[[The Unspeakable Act]]'' ||\n|-\n|rowspan=2| 2019 || ''[[Fourteen (film)|Fourteen]]'' || \n|-\n| ''Caterina'' || Short\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== 